------------------------------------------------------------------------
7. NETWORK-LEVEL CONNECTIVITY vs BILL-LEVEL CO-AFFILIATION
------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Bill-level: same lobbyist/firm appears on both companies' first-quarter
  reports FOR THAT SPECIFIC BILL. Network-level: companies share any
  lobbyist/firm across their FULL lobbying portfolios.

  Finding: direct bill-level co-affiliation is rare; most RBO influence
  pairs are not connected even at the portfolio level — the RBO network
  captures a broader coordination signal (Carpenter et al. 1998).

  Directed bill pairs (n=3,184):
  Channel                                    Bill-level    Network-level
  --------------------------------------------------------------------
  Lobbyist                                     6 ( 0.2%)      19 ( 0.6%)
  Firm (external K-street)                     3 ( 0.1%)      13 ( 0.4%)
  Any                                          7 ( 0.2%)      20 ( 0.6%)

  Lobbyist-network lag (n=19):  mean=2.37 q  vs  non-connected mean=2.04 q
    Mann-Whitney U (connected < non-connected):  p=0.6496
  Firm-network lag (n=13):  mean=1.92 q  vs  non-connected mean=2.05 q
    Mann-Whitney U (connected < non-connected):  p=0.4522

------------------------------------------------------------------------
8. ALIGNMENT TEST: DO MEDIATED BILLS CONFIRM THE RBO EDGE DIRECTION?
------------------------------------------------------------------------
  For directed RBO edges (balanced=0), check whether the bill-level
  leader (first adopter) is also the RBO edge source — i.e., whether
  affiliation-mediated bills are consistent with the aggregate direction.

  If shared affiliation channels information from influencer to follower,
  mediated bills should more often have rbo_source as the leader.

  All directed bills (n=2,960):
    Leader == RBO source:  2,808 / 2,960  (94.9%)
    Binomial test (rate > 0.5):  p=0.0000
  Non-mediated directed bills (n=2,953):
    Leader == RBO source:  2,801 / 2,953  (94.9%)
    Binomial test (rate > 0.5):  p=0.0000
  Any-mediated directed bills (n=7):
    Leader == RBO source:  7 / 7  (100.0%)
    Binomial test (rate > 0.5):  p=0.0078
  Lobbyist-mediated bills (n=6):
    Leader == RBO source:  6 / 6  (100.0%)
    Binomial test (rate > 0.5):  p=0.0156
  Firm-mediated bills (n=3):
    Leader == RBO source:  3 / 3  (100.0%)
    Binomial test (rate > 0.5):  p=0.1250

